German Benchmark Stocks Gain; BMW, Volkswagen Rise as Commerzbank Drops

-- B y   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-04-13T15:58:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/sap-tag-immobilien-thyssenkrupp-german-equity-preview.html
German stocks rose for the first
time this week after a report that showed European industrial
production growth accelerated in February.  Bayerische Motoren Werke AG (BMW)  and  Volkswagen AG (VOW)  led European
carmakers higher.  HeidelbergCement AG (HEI)  jumped as Exane BNP
Paribas recommended the stock.  Commerzbank AG (CBK)  slumped 5 percent
as it sold conditional mandatory exchangeable notes, or Comen,
to investors.  The DAX Index gained 1.1 percent to 7,177.97 at the 5:30
p.m. close in  Frankfurt . The measure, which slumped 1.4 percent
yesterday as  Japan  raised its nuclear radiation warning and
Alcoa Inc.’s sales missed analysts’ estimates, has declined 3.4
percent from this year’s high on Feb. 18.  Production in the 17-member euro area rose for a fifth
straight month, increasing 0.4 percent from January, when it
advanced 0.2 percent, the European Union’s statistics office in
Luxembourg said today. Economists had forecast a gain of 0.8
percent, the median of 34 estimates in a Bloomberg News survey
showed. Production jumped 7.3 from February 2010.  In the U.S., the world’s biggest economy, retail sales rose
in March for a ninth consecutive month, showing that the
improving job market has helped Americans cope with higher costs
for fuel and food.  Deutsche Bank AG,  Germany ’s biggest bank, rose 1.6 percent
to 42.69 euros. JPMorgan Chase & Co., the second-largest  U.S.
bank  by assets, said first-quarter profit rose 67 percent to a
record, beating analysts’ estimates, as its provisions for bad
mortgages and credit-card loans fell.  ThyssenKrupp rallied 1.4 percent to 29.82 euros, trimming
yesterday’s retreat. Germany’s biggest steelmaker may sell
“several billion euros” of units to reduce debt and expand its
technology business, the Financial Times Deutschland reported,
without saying where it got the information.  BMW, VW  BMW, the world’s biggest maker of luxury cars, climbed 1.7
percent to 57.59 euros, ending five days of declines.
Volkswagen, Europe’s largest carmaker, added 2.7 percent to
111.60 euros. Daimler AG gained 1.3 percent to 51.10 euros.
European carmakers were among the best performers in the
benchmark Stoxx  Europe  600 Index today, rising 1.5 percent.  HeidelbergCement jumped 4 percent to 50.39 euros, the
highest price in a month, as the cement maker was upgraded to
“outperform” from “neutral” at Exane. The brokerage raised
its recommendation on the building materials sector to
“outperform.”  Commerzbank, Germany’s second-biggest lender, dropped 5
percent to 4.69 euros, the lowest price since July 2009. The
company may have priced its conditional mandatory exchangeable
notes, or Comen, at a minimum of 4.25 euros apiece, according to
three people familiar with the offer.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Julie Cruz in Frankfurt at 
